I've got a few related modules that I'm documenting and I'm trying to link between them.  I control the format and publishing of the documentation of each module so it's all very predictable.  Docs are generated during a CI publish step and published to `gh-pages`.

I have followed the very useful docs on [third party symbols](https://github.com/TypeStrong/typedoc/blob/master/internal-docs/third-party-symbols.md) and have configured an unknown symbol resolver which works well.

I had an idea that if module A uses some of the types from module B, module B could include URLs for the docs of those types in it's package.json which my unknown symbol resolver could read while generating the docs for module A.

So, in module A:

```ts
import { SomeType } from 'module-b'

export default function () {
  return new SomeType()
}
```

Then in module B's package.json what I'm trying to generate is something like:

```js
{
  // other stuff
  "typedocs": {
    "SomeType": "https://......SomeType.html"
  }
}
```

Then my plugin is something like (not really, it's a bit more complicated in reality):

```js
function load (Application) {
  Application.converter.addUnknownSymbolResolver((ref) => {
      const moduleName = ref.moduleSource
      const symbolName = ref.symbolReference.path[0].path
      const manifest = require(`${moduleName}/package.json`)

      return (manifest.typedocs ?? {})[symbolName]
  })
}
```

The URLs generated by typedoc are predictable based on the type, name and path of the export, so I think it could be guessed from the `DeclarationReflection`s in the project `Context` object, but is there a way to hook in to the template output to build a list of symbol -> doc path mappings?

Another approach, though fragile, might just be reading the file names of the generated HTML docs and deriving it all from there?

The TypeDoc docs [describe how to link to third party symbols](https://github.com/TypeStrong/typedoc/blob/master/internal-docs/third-party-symbols.md) so this PR adds the beginning of support for that.

It adds a plugin with links to the docs of a few well-known types which will be used to link through to their definitions in generated docs.

It also adds the ability for third party modules to declare their own docs in their manifests.  For example for `@multiformats/multiaddr` to make use of the `Multiaddr` interface linkable in the documentation of other modules, it needs to add the following to it's `package.json`:

```js
{
  // ... other stuff
  "docs": {
    "Multiaddr": "https://multiformats.github.io/js-multiaddr/interfaces/index.Multiaddr.html"
  }
}
```

Creating as a draft because we need a bit more done on this before it's ready.

- [ ] Is `"docs"` ok for a package.json field?  Should be something else?
- [ ] We should generate the `"docs"` field for aegir-managed modules during the release process, this will probably involve adding another plugin that collects the links for generated types and prefixes them with the eventual `gh-pages` url for the current repo
- [ ] It needs testing with modules that have more complex exports

